<LP>
   NEW YORK -- The bond market was whipsawed yesterday,
initially battered by rising interest rates abroad then
rebounding as U.S. stock prices plunged.
   Ultimately, the bond market ended unchanged to moderately
lower with the Treasury's benchmark 30-year bond posting a
1/4 point decline, or a loss of $2.50 for a bond with a
$1,000 face amount.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "It was a very volatile and choppy trading day," said
James Capra, senior vice president at Shearson Lehman
Government Securities Inc.
   The bond market opened sharply lower with prices falling
as much as 3/4 point in reaction to rising interest rates in
Japan. Yields on Japan's benchmark 10-year bond rose to a
six-year high of 7.475% yesterday, even though Japan's
central bank tried to stabilize rates.
   The increase in Japanese bond yields revived fears that
Japanese investors, traditionally big buyers of U.S. Treasury
bonds, may not participate aggressively in next month's
multibillion-dollar quarterly Treasury-bond auction.
   The Treasury's 10-year bond now yields just one percentage
point more than Japan's 10-year bond, which some analysts say
is too small of a spread to encourage Japan's big
institutional investors to buy U.S. Treasurys.
   The bond market then abruptly shifted gears as a plunge of
more than 100 points in the Dow Jones Industrial Average took
center stage.
   "When you got the swan dive in the stock market, traders
were climbing all over themselves to buy bonds," said F. Ward
McCarthy, a managing director at Stone &amp; McCarthy Research
Associates, Princeton, N.J.
   The stock sell-off prompted some "flight-to-quality"
buying among nervous institutional investors who sold stocks
and reinvested the cash in the bond market. The Dow Jones
Industrial Average staged a partial rebound later in the day
and ended at 2904.70, down 56.44 points.
   "If investors are getting out of stocks, then governments
are the safest available alternative," said Charles
Lieberman, a managing director at Manufacturers Hanover
Securities Corp.
   The bond rebound was not only the product of modest
flight-to-quality buying, but also of traders reversing their
bets on the market.
   Alan McClymonds, co-head of government trading at First
Boston Corp., described yesterday's market as "vicious"
because many bond speculators lost large sums of money.
   In early trading, many speculators took on short
positions. In a short sale, dealers and speculators sell
borrowed securities and later seek to make a profit by
replacing what was borrowed with cheaper securities.
   But when bond prices rose yesterday, these speculators
were forced to cover their money-losing short positions by
buying bonds at higher prices.
   The losses didn't stop there. Mr. Capra at Shearson Lehman
said speculators continued to buy bonds in a bet that stocks
would fall further and lead to even higher bond prices. They
were wrong again.
   "The speculative side was in and out and lost money both
ways," said Shearson Lehman's Mr. Capra.
   The bond rally stalled out late in the day, however, as
investors turned their attention to the bond market's
numerous negative fundamentals. In addition to rising
Japanese bond yields, investors are worried that
budget-cutting negotiations between Congress and the White
House have stalled and that the Federal Reserve appears to be
abandoning its battle against inflation.
                                                                                                       

   Treasury Securities
                                                                                                       

   Treasury bonds ended little changed to lower in volatile
trading.
   The benchmark 30-year bond ended at a price of 102, down
from 102 7/32 on Friday. The issue's yield rose to 8.55% from
8.53% on Friday. Two-year notes were quoted at 100 15/32
compared with 100 16/32 on Friday. The yield was unchanged at
8.07%.
   Meanwhile, at the government's weekly Treasury bill
auction short-term rates were set sharply lower.
   The average discount rate on three-month Treasury bills
was 7.49% at yesterday's auction while the rate on six-month
bills was 7.40%. Those rates were down from last week's
auction when they were 7.62% and 7.52%, respectively.
   The average rate on three-month bills was the lowest since
the average of 7.37% at the auction on Oct. 16 while the rate
on six-month bills was the lowest since the average of 7.30%
at the auction on Dec. 4, 1989.
