   Corporate Bonds
                                                                                                       

   The tumble in stock prices rattled the junk bond market,
sending the high-yield speculative-grade securities
moderately lower.
   Most junk bonds finished the session down 1/4 point to 3/8
point, the declines were modest compared to the sell-off in
the stock market.
   Among the high-yield bonds which ended the day lower were
pay-in-kind bonds of RJR Nabisco Inc. Pay-in-kind bonds pay
interest in the form of additional securities. The company's
17 3/8% convertible pay-in-kind debentures, which previously
carried an interest rate of 14.07%, finished down 3/4 points
to close at 117 on the New York Stock Exchange. The 17%
exchangeable pay-in-kind debentures, which also had a coupon
rate of 14.07%, ended down 1 point at 94 1/4.
   The junk bonds of R.H. Macy &amp; Co. continued to gain after
news that the New York-based retailer asked investment banks
to suggest ways for it to reduce debt and raise money. Macy's
14.5% senior subordinated debentures added 1 point to close
at 76.
   Time Warner Inc.'s convertible preferred stock slipped
after it reported a second-quarter loss of $51 million. The
company's 8 3/4% convertible preferred stock Series C ended
down 1/4 point at 42 1/8.
   Among new issues in the investment grade market, Spain
received an enthusiastic welcome when it tapped the corporate
debt market with its first underwritten U.S. debt offering.
   Spain offered $300 million of 10-year notes which were
priced to yield 9.125%.
   Mark Seigel, managing director in the syndicate department
at lead underwriter Morgan Stanley &amp; Co., said the offering
received such a rousing response from investors because it
represents "the first opportunity for institutional investors
to purchase a discrete Yankee bond offering" from the Kingdom
of Spain.

   Municipal Securities
                                                                                                       

   Tax-exempt issues ended unchanged to 1/8 point lower, with
some issues off 1/4 point in spots.
   In secondary trading, the New Jersey Turnpike Authority's
7.20% securities of 2018 were unchanged at 99 1/2 to yield
7.22%.
   No large new municipal issues were priced during the
session.
   Looking ahead on the calendar, New York City will sell
$1.1 billion of tax anticipation notes via competitive bid
today.
                                                                                                       

   Foreign Bonds
                                                                                                       

   Japanese bond yields hit a six-year high yesterday as
investors reacted negatively to a move by the Bank of Japan,
the nation's central bank.
   The BOJ bought a total of 500 billion yen ($3.36 billion)
of overnight commercial paper in two separate purchases. A
Bank of Japan official said the central bank was trying to
offset a rise in rates after the markets misread a 1.2
trillion yen bank loan call the central bank made last
Friday. He said the loan call was meant to drain excess bank
reserves, and not a signal that short-term interest rates
should rise.
   But investors interpreted yesterday's action as a
flip-flop in policy. "The BOJ reversed the move they made
last week, which made the market even more upset because {the
Bank of Japan} is flopping back and forth and is
untrustworthy," said a dealer at a foreign-based securities
firm. "The market is still negative about rates," said
another dealer.
   At the official 3:00 p.m. JST close of the Tokyo Stock
Exchange, Japan's benchmark No. 119 10-year bond was quoted
at a price of 85.75, down 0.45 points, to yield 7.47%,
according to Japan's Daiwa Securities Co. That yield was the
highest for a benchmark 10-year bond in six years. During
over-the-counter trading, after the Tokyo Stock Exchange
closed, the yield on the benchmark bond rose further to
7.48%. (Japanese bond yields are quoted here in local terms.
However, when calculated using the semiannual compound
measure to compare yields across markets, the yield on the
No. 119 bond was 6.97%, according to Salomon Brothers Inc.,
New York.)
   Japanese rates on new three-month certificates of deposit
were unchanged yesterday at 7.7%. Corresponding Euroyen
deposits, which are securities sold in Europe that pay
interest in yen, were also flat at around 7.69%.
                                                                                                       

   Mortgage, Asset-Backed Securities
                                                                                                       

   Mortgage securities ended little changed.
   Among actively traded secondary issues, Government
National Mortgage Association 9.5% issues were off 1/32 at 99
3/4 to yield 9.67%. Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp. 9.5%
issues were unchanged at 99 3/ 32 and Federal National
Mortgage Association 9.5% securities were flat at 99 19/32.
   In the primary market, trading began in two new issues, a
real estate mortgage investment conduit and an asset-backed
offering.
   Fannie Mae unveiled details of a $500 million Remic
mortgage issue, offered by Kidder, Peabody &amp; Co. and backed
by 9.5% Fannie Mae mortgage-backed securities.
   And Sears Receivables Financing Group, a unit of Sears,
Roebuck &amp; Co., is offering $250 million of securities backed
by credit-card receivables with a coupon rate of 8.70% that
were priced at 99.855 to yield 8.75%.
